3. High Level Design

    Basic architecture flow:

        User → DNS → Nearest Edge Server → Cache
                                            |
                                            | (cache miss)
                                            ↓
                                            Regional Server
                                            |
                                            | (cache miss)
                                            ↓
                                            Origin Server

    Cache Hierarchy (Multi-Layer Caching)

        User
        ↓
        Edge Cache (L1)
        ↓
        Regional Cache (L2)
        ↓
        Origin Server



    Different Caching Strategy


        1. PULL CDN (On Demand Retrival):

            Benifits:

                -> Efficient resource utilization
                -> Dynamic content support
                -> scalability
                -> Lower bandwidth usage


            Cost:

                -> Latency per cache misses
                -> Overhead on origin server
                -> Freshness of content

        
        2. PUSH CDN (On Demand Retrival)

            Benefits:

                -> Low Latency
                -> Reduced origin server load
                -> Optimized for static content

            Costs:

                -> Resource utilization and long tail
                -> Limited dynamic content support
                -> Potential for stale data

            
        3. PULL CDN & PUSH CDN (Hybrid)

            -> PUSH only popular content

            -> PULL only on demand content


